      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a priority notice in a Queensland property transaction?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A priority notice is a temporary lodgement on a Queensland property title that protects a buyer's interest for up to 60 days after exchange. It prevents the seller from transferring the title to another party, granting new mortgages, or dealing with the property in ways that could undermine the buyer's position before settlement."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does a priority notice affect the seller during the settlement period?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Once a buyer lodges a priority notice, the seller cannot refinance the property, grant a new mortgage, or transfer title to another buyer during the notice period. These restrictions are routine in a normal settlement but become relevant if the seller needs to do any title dealings during the contract period."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What happens to a priority notice at settlement?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A priority notice is discharged automatically when the buyer's transfer of title is registered at settlement. The buyer's solicitor handles this as part of the normal settlement process through PEXA or equivalent electronic lodgement. Sellers do not need to take any separate action."
      }
    }
  ]
