      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers &middot; 5 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Priority Notices in Queensland Property Transactions: What Sellers Should Know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        A priority notice is a routine but often misunderstood step in Queensland conveyancing. Understanding what it does, what it prevents, and how it resolves helps sellers move through settlement with fewer surprises.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Most sellers hear the term priority notice for the first time when their solicitor mentions it after contracts are exchanged. It sounds more complicated than it is. A priority notice is a standard protective mechanism in Queensland property law that is lodged on a title by the buyer's solicitor after exchange to protect the buyer's interest during the settlement period. For sellers in a straightforward transaction, it does not change what they need to do between exchange and settlement. But it does impose specific restrictions on what a seller can do with the title during that window, and understanding those restrictions avoids unnecessary complications.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a priority notice actually does</h2>
      <p>When a buyer lodges a priority notice, it appears as a lodgement on the title in the Queensland Titles Registry. The effect is to put anyone searching the title on notice that a buyer has a contractual interest in the property. More practically, it creates a priority position for the buyer: any instrument lodged after the priority notice (other than certain permitted dealings) will rank behind the buyer's eventual transfer of title.</p>

      <p>This matters in the rare circumstances where a seller might attempt to deal with the property in a way that would harm the buyer. For example, granting a new mortgage, transferring to a different buyer, or lodging other dealings that affect title. The priority notice prevents these from taking effect ahead of the buyer's transfer. In practice, this is almost never a deliberate act by sellers. The notice is lodged as a matter of routine, not because buyers are suspicious of the specific seller. It is simply the standard protective step that buyers' solicitors take in every Queensland transaction.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers cannot do once a priority notice is lodged</h2>
      <p>This is where understanding the mechanics matters. Once a priority notice is on the title, the seller cannot refinance the property with a new lender, grant a new mortgage over the property, or transfer title to a different buyer. The seller also cannot lodge most other dealings that would affect the title during the notice period.</p>

      <p>For most sellers, none of these restrictions cause any practical problem. If you have sold and you are in the process of settling, you are not typically in the market for a new mortgage on the property you are selling. The restriction is designed to prevent the specific scenarios that would harm the buyer, not to create administrative burdens for honest sellers in normal circumstances.</p>

      <p>Where the restriction occasionally becomes relevant is when a seller needs to refinance their existing mortgage or draw down a new facility during the settlement period, typically when they are simultaneously purchasing another property and need to restructure their borrowings. If this applies to your situation, your solicitor needs to know before exchange so they can plan the sequence of settlements carefully. There are ways to manage this, but it requires coordination between your solicitor, the buyer's solicitor, and your lender. It is not something to work out after the priority notice has been lodged.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The 60-day window and what happens if settlement extends</h2>
      <p>A priority notice in Queensland is valid for 60 days from the date of lodgement. In most residential transactions, settlement occurs well within that window. Standard Queensland contract settlement periods are 30 to 45 days, which gives comfortable clearance in most cases.</p>

      <p>If settlement is delayed beyond the 60-day window, the buyer's solicitor will need to lodge a new priority notice to maintain the buyer's protected position. This is straightforward in most cases but does require the buyer's solicitor to act before the original notice lapses. If you are the seller and the settlement is running late, this is something your solicitor should be monitoring on your behalf, but it is worth being aware of as a potential administrative step if the transaction extends.</p>

      <p>Delays beyond 60 days are uncommon in standard residential sales but do occur, particularly where finance approval takes longer than anticipated, where one party has difficulty meeting a pre-settlement condition, or where there is a dispute about a condition in the contract. If a delay is expected, both solicitors should be communicating proactively about the priority notice position.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When the priority notice is lodged</h2>
      <p>The buyer's solicitor typically lodges the priority notice shortly after exchange of contracts. In Queensland, exchange occurs when both the buyer and seller have signed the contract and it has been dated. The priority notice is not lodged at the same time as exchange in most cases. It is lodged as a separate step by the buyer's solicitor, usually within the first few days after exchange once the solicitor has confirmed the contract is unconditional or is proceeding toward becoming unconditional.</p>

      <p>You will not necessarily be notified the moment the priority notice is lodged. Your solicitor will be aware of it because it is visible on any title search, and it is a standard expectation in Queensland conveyancing that it will be lodged. There is no action required of you when it appears. It simply means the buyer has taken the standard protective step and the transaction is proceeding normally.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How the priority notice resolves at settlement</h2>
      <p>The priority notice is discharged automatically when the buyer's transfer of title is registered at settlement. In Queensland, residential settlements are now conducted predominantly through PEXA, the electronic lodgement network. At settlement, the buyer's transfer documents and the discharge of any existing seller's mortgage are lodged simultaneously, and the title transfers. The priority notice is superseded by the registered transfer and no longer appears as an encumbrance.</p>

      <p>Sellers do not need to take any separate action to remove the priority notice. It is not something that lingers on the title after settlement. It resolves cleanly as part of the normal settlement process, and the buyer receives a clean registered title with no residual notice remaining.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How your solicitor manages priority notices as routine</h2>
      <p>For experienced Queensland property solicitors, priority notices are an unremarkable part of every transaction. They lodge them for buyers as a matter of course, and they manage them as sellers without any particular concern. If you are selling in Brisbane and your solicitor is experienced in Queensland residential conveyancing, you will typically not even need to think about the priority notice once you have been briefed on what it means.</p>

      <p>Where problems occasionally arise is when sellers are not briefed at all and then become alarmed when they see an unfamiliar lodgement on a title search. If you search your own title during the settlement period and see the priority notice, it should not cause concern. It is a normal part of the process. If you have questions about it, your solicitor is the right person to ask, not your agent. The agent's role is to help you through the commercial side of the transaction. Your solicitor manages the legal and title mechanics.</p>

